Penn Treaty Park is a historic and scenic green space located on the western bank of the Delaware River in the Fishtown neighborhood of Philadelphia. The park is celebrated for its connection to Pennsylvania founder William Penn‚Äôs legendary 1683 treaty of peace with the Lenape tribe under an elm tree, symbolizing a commitment to friendship and coexistence. Today, the park offers a peaceful retreat with walking paths, shaded areas, and open spaces favored by dog walkers and picnickers. Visitors can enjoy unobstructed views of the Benjamin Franklin Bridge and reflect on the area‚Äôs rich history, marked by a statue of William Penn and the enduring legacy of the Penn‚Äôs Creek Massacre of 1755. Penn Treaty Park stands as a testament to the city‚Äôs past and a cherished urban oasis for residents and visitors alike.

I love this place. The people and the atmosphere are incredible. Every time I visit this park it reminds me of Franklin Park in Boston and Central Park in NY. Except that Penn Treaty is a lot smaller, of course. However; there is one problem that I have noticed, and that's the illegal mountain bikes and 4 wheelers that I have seen cruising through the walkways. These young people are usually showing off and they can hurt somebody. That's the only reason I didn't give the park a 5 star review. Like I said, the park is beautiful and it's getting better all the time and the people are a mix of all races and backgrounds. It's a great place to have a relaxing time with your wife, girlfriend, husband, or partner. I have visited this place for many years and I have never had an argument with anybody, but I have met some wonderful people and made some good friends.
There is one thing I must warn about. There's no bathroom anywhere in the park. You must walk to the Sugar House Casino to use their facility. If you do come, I hope you have a great time.

Penn Treaty Park is great for a quick walk, walking your dog or having a picnic.  It can get very crowded in the warmer months.  Sometimes you have to contend with people that insist on riding motorized bikes or small motorcycles in the park.  There is very little security or police presence and they generally look the other way anyway.  Parking in the summer months can be limited and difficult as well.  The park is better during the work week, early mornings and during the fall/winter months.  Development is encroaching on the park which is a blessing and a curse.  There were ramblings about Live Nation Events getting involved with the park which I am vehemently against!

Penn Treaty is one of my morning go to spots. Avoid on weekends if you're trying to remain socially distant. Go on week days or early mornings. When the park first opens up it's usually pretty laid back with lots of space to run, cycle, or workout on the grass. As the day progresses the park fills in and gets a little overcrowded. The new updates along the waterfront provide a lot more options for those looking to find a quiet spot to meditate in the mornings. I recommend being careful along the rocky areas along the water because there are a ton of rats that roam around if you look closely you'll see them! Aside from the rats, this park is great. There are some beautiful views along the path and there is a spot at the back where you could probably launch a kayak or sup if you go early enough to do so, just note that this is not publicly listed as a launch spot.

I've been coming to Penn Treaty Park since I was a small child, it's always been a good experience for me. They recently added a new path from the park to the casino and the construction looks good. The park has always been a great place for sunrises and sunsets on the Delaware river. It's a great place for photography too especially in the winter when the river freezes over. The playground is pretty new. It's definitely one of the better public playgrounds in the entire area. There area paths for walking and biking and a large field for other activities. Penn treaty park is great for friends and family or a nice place to get some peace especially in the early morning hours. There are benches and tables for picnicking and family gatherings. The only thing this place lacks consistently is a public bathroom, there are plenty of times when you will find a porta potty or two but sometimes the potties are gone so be sure to use the restroom before coming to the park.

From Penn Treaty Park, you have an amazing view of the Ben Franklin Bridge. The park has a playground and plenty of room to run on grass. It's not the nicest park in Philly, nor is it very large, but it's worth it for the views. My biggest issue with the park is not the homeless people you may spot on a bench, but the fact that dog owners like to let their dogs off leash in this park even though there is no fenced in dog park, which is illegal. As the owner of an older dog who has gotten more selective with his friend choices, this particularly bothers me as I don't like having strange unleashed dogs run up on us. However, if you're visiting Philly, I really do recommend stopping for the view. It's the perfect spot for a photo of the Ben Franklin Bridge.
